## 1. Purpose

This playbook establishes the detection, classification, and response procedures for Shadow AI within {{ business_name }}. Shadow AI poses significant risks to data protection, regulatory compliance, and organisational security. This playbook ensures that unauthorised AI usage is identified rapidly, assessed proportionately, and resolved in alignment with the **Privacy Act 1988**, the **POLA Act 2024**, and the **AI6 Guidance for AI Adoption** (October 2024).

---

## 2. Scope

This playbook applies to:

- All employees, contractors, and third parties operating within {{ business_name }}'s IT environment
- All AI-powered tools, platforms, APIs, browser extensions, and mobile applications
- AI features embedded within approved software that have not been separately assessed
- Personal devices used to process {{ business_name }}'s data through AI services (BYOD)

---

## 3. Definitions

| Term | Definition |
|------|-----------|
| Shadow AI | Any AI tool, service, or feature used to process {{ business_name }}'s data without formal approval through the AI procurement process |
| Sanctioned AI | AI tools that have been evaluated, approved, and onboarded per the {{ business_name }} AI Procurement Policy |
| Tolerated AI | Shadow AI that has been discovered, risk-assessed, and temporarily permitted pending formal evaluation |
| Prohibited AI | AI tools that have been assessed and explicitly banned due to unacceptable risk |

---

## 4. Detection Methods

{{ business_name }} employs the following methods to identify Shadow AI usage:

### 4.1 Technical Detection

| Method | Description | Frequency |
|--------|------------|-----------|
| DNS monitoring | Monitor DNS queries to known AI service domains (e.g., api.openai.com, bard.google.com, claude.ai) | Continuous |
| Proxy / firewall logs | Analyse outbound web traffic for connections to AI platforms | Daily review |
| Endpoint agents | Deploy endpoint detection to identify AI desktop applications and browser extensions | Continuous |
| DLP integration | Data Loss Prevention alerts triggered by data uploads to AI services | Continuous |
| SaaS discovery tools | Cloud access security broker (CASB) scanning for unauthorised SaaS AI subscriptions | Weekly |
| API gateway monitoring | Detect outbound API calls to AI model endpoints from internal systems | Continuous |

### 4.2 Administrative Detection

| Method | Description | Frequency |
|--------|------------|-----------|
| Expense report review | Flag payments to AI vendors (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google AI, Midjourney, etc.) | Monthly |
| Credit card reconciliation | Identify AI service charges on corporate cards | Monthly |
| Employee surveys | Anonymous surveys asking about AI tool usage | Quarterly |
| IT helpdesk analysis | Review tickets mentioning AI tools not in the sanctioned register | Ongoing |
| Vendor contract review | Identify AI features embedded in existing vendor platforms | During renewal |

