## 5. Risk Classification

When Shadow AI is discovered, classify it according to the following matrix:

### 5.1 Classification Matrix

| Risk Level | Criteria | Examples |
|------------|----------|----------|
| **Critical** | Processes Restricted or sensitive personal information; makes automated decisions affecting individuals; data sent overseas without APP 8 safeguards | Medical AI processing health records; AI screening job applicants with personal data |
| **High** | Processes Confidential data; no DPA in place; vendor trains models on customer data; no model training opt-out | Uploading financial reports to ChatGPT; using AI transcription for confidential meetings |
| **Medium** | Processes Internal data; vendor has reasonable security but has not been formally assessed | Using AI writing assistants for internal communications; AI-powered scheduling tools |
| **Low** | Processes only Public data; no personal information involved; tool operates locally | AI-powered spell checkers (offline); code autocompletion on public repositories |

### 5.2 Escalation Factors

The following factors increase the risk classification by one level:

- The tool has been in use for more than 30 days without detection
- Multiple employees are using the same unapproved tool
- The tool is processing data types including: {% for dtype in data_types_processed %}{{ dtype }}{% if not loop.last %}, {% endif %}{% endfor %}
{% if ai_profiling_or_eligibility %}- The tool is used for profiling or eligibility decisions{% endif %}
{% if customer_facing_ai %}- The tool interacts directly with customers{% endif %}

